To solve this, we first notice the pattern that for every integer $n$.
\begin{align*}f(1)&=1 \\\\f(2\cdot1+1)&=f(1)+1\\\\&=2\\\\f(2\cdot2+1)&=f(2)+1\\\\&=f(2\cdot 1+1)+1\\\\&=f(1)+2\\\\&=3\\&\vdots\\\\f(2n+1)&=f(n)+1\end{align*}
From this we can notice that $f(2n+1)=f(n)+1$ is very reminiscent of the recursion relation for addition of natural numbers, written for addition in reverse: instead of adding numbers we iterate $f(n)$ performing $n$stractions. The $1$ in this iteration is our increment or hop. Since the proposed scheme is etmostly like addition, we can easily see that $f(n)=\text{length of }

ni the path from $n$ to $1$ by following the recurrence. First, we factor $15$ into powers of $2$:
\begin{align*}15&=2\cdot7+1\\\\&=2\cdot 2\cdot3+1\\\\&=2\cdot 2  \cdot2 \cdot1+1
\end{align*}
We can see that $15$ factors to four times $2$ and one times $1$. Also, from above: $f(2n+1)=f(n)+1$ which explains, from top to bottom, $f(15)=f(3)+1=2+f(1)=3$. The path from $15$ to $1$ is: $15\mapsto 2\cdot15+1\mapsto 2^2\cdot(2\cdot 15+1)+1\mapsto 2^3\cdot3+1$. Each number in this arrowing process, like $15,3,3+1,f(3)+1$ causes us to head towards $1$ by $1$ each time. Recalling that $f(1)=1$, this means from the bottom up:
$$f(3+1)=2+f(1)=3\\f(2\cdot(3+1)+1)=f(3)+1=2\\f(2\cdot2\cdot(3+1)+1)=f(2)+(3+1)=3$$
Therefore, $f(15)=\color{silver}{3}$. <answer> $3$. </answer>

